VWhat has the War on Drugs  done to the world?
p4
aVLook at the murder and mayhem in Mexico,
p5
aVCentral America, so many  other parts of the planet,
p6
aVthe global black market estimated
p7
aVat 300 billion dollars a year,
p8
aVprisons packed in the  United States and elsewhere,
p9
aVpolice and military drawn  into an unwinnable war
p10
aVthat violates basic rights,  and ordinary citizens
p11
aVjust hope they don't get  caught in the crossfire,
p12
aVand meanwhile, more people using
p13
aVmore drugs than ever.
p14
aVIt's my country's history  with alcohol prohibition
p15
aVand Al Capone, times 50.
p16
aa(lp17
VWhich is why it's  particularly galling to me
p18
aVas an American that we've  been the driving force
p19
aVbehind this global drug war.
p20
aVAsk why so many countries criminalize
p21
aVdrugs they'd never heard of,
p22
aVwhy the U.N. drug treaties emphasize
p23
aVcriminalization over health,
p24
aVeven why most of the money worldwide
p25
aVfor dealing with drug abuse goes not
p26
aVto helping agencies but those that punish,
p27
aVand you'll find the good old U.S. of A.
p28
aa(lp29
VWhy did we do this?
p30
aVSome people, especially in Latin America,
p31
aVthink it's not really about drugs.
p32
aVIt's just a subterfuge for advancing
p33
aVthe realpolitik interests of the U.S.
p34
aVBut by and large, that's not it.
p35
aVWe don't want gangsters and guerrillas
p36
aVfunded with illegal drug money
p37
aVterrorizing and taking over other nations.
p38
aVNo, the fact is, America really is crazy
p39
aVwhen it comes to drugs.
p40
aVI mean, don't forget, we're  the ones who thought
p41
aVthat we could prohibit alcohol.
p42
aVSo think about our global drug war
p43
aVnot as any sort of rational policy,
p44
aVbut as the international projection
p45
aVof a domestic psychosis.
p46
aV(Applause)
